article.headline: Syracuse 69, UTEP 56
article.story: SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- The Big East beckons. Syracuse is as ready as it'll ever be. Eric Devendorf had 16 points, Gerry McNamara had 14 points and 10 assists, and the Orange beat Texas-El Paso 69-56 on Wednesday night. It was the final nonconference game and the ninth straight win for the Orange, (12-2), who open Big East play at home against South Florida on Sunday afternoon. "Our schedule is difficult, we know that," Syracuse coach Jim Boeheim said. "We're not going into the Big East off six or seven easy wins. We've had to battle. Now we've got more of the same ahead of us." This certainly was a battle -- until a second-half Syracuse rally broke open a tight game against UTEP (7-5) in the first game between the schools. Syracuse used a smothering man-to-man defense to slow the transition game of the Miners, who twice rallied from 10 points down in the first half and went into the locker room at the break trailing 35-34. After Miguel Ayala drained a 3-pointer to tie it at 44-all with 13:20 left, the Orange clamped down defensively. While UTEP had five misses and three turnovers in a span of nearly nine minutes, Syracuse put away the game with a 17-5 run. "Man-to-man gave us a lot of energy, it made us play harder," said McNamara, who leads the Orange with five double-doubles. "When we start doing that, good things usually happen." Demetris Nichols finished with 11 points and Terrence Roberts had nine points and nine rebounds for the Orange. Ayala led the Miners with 19 points off the bench, and Will Kimble and Edgar Moreno each had 10. Nichols hit a jumper in the lane, Roberts converted a follow slam, and McNamara made a runner in the lane to give Syracuse a six-point lead. A 3-pointer by Nichols and another 3 by McNamara, his first of the game after seven misses, made it 58-49 with 6:51 left and Louie McCroskey's layup 26 seconds later gave the Orange an 11-point cushion. "You get it to 44-all, I think we got a little too excited," said UTEP coach Doc Sadler, whose last two losses have come against two Hall of Fame coaches, Boeheim and Bob Knight of Texas Tech. "You're not going to score in transition against Syracuse at their place. I thought we forced the issue. Even when we got it down there, we took some bad shots." John Tofi, who was averaging 15.4 points, did not score, and Jason Williams went 2-for-7, both baskets coming late, to score 10 points, five below his average. "They did a great job on me," said Tofi, who was 0-for-6 shooting. "I never got a clear shot off. They contested every shot." Despite their current winning streak, the Orange remain unranked and undeterred. "We've shown glimpses of really good play, 30 to 35 minutes," said McNamara, who has 538 assists, one behind Eddie Moss for fifth place all-time at Syracuse. "Now we have to concentrate on playing 40 minutes. If we do that, I think we can beat anybody." Devendorf scored twice at the start of the second half but sat out the rest of the period after picking up his fourth foul at 13:31. It was his second straight game with 16 points though, and that's a good sign for the freshman guard. "Knowing my place, trying to fit into the team, that's what I've done," said Devendorf, who has started every game during the Orange's winning streak. "I just feel more comfortable playing, and that's what has helped me out a lot. I'm definitely ready for the Big East. I'm as comfortable as I can be, I think." The Miners struggled early against the Syracuse zone, missing their first eight shots and falling behind 11-1. UTEP didn't get a basket until Moreno hit a foul-line jumper 6:19 into the game. But 23 seconds later, Kimble converted a three-point play, Ayala followed with a 3-pointer, and Williams hit two free throws to cut the Orange lead to 16-12. Syracuse rebuilt the lead to 10 on a 3-pointer by Devendorf midway through the period, but the Miners would not go away. They hit 10 of their final 19 shots to pull within a point at the break. UTEP scored 15 points off Syracuse's 10 turnovers in the period and went on a 16-6 spurt to tie the game at 28-28 with 4:32 left. Ayala, who had 11 points in the half, hit a 3 from the right corner to begin the run, Kevin Henderson followed with a steal and layup, and Kimble converted three baskets in close to even the score.
